This document has been drawn in a standard form and provides that you will purchase the property at the price of   £295,000.00   (no VAT will be payable on this).   The price includes the items shown on the Fixtures and Fittings list mentioned below which will be attached to the contract. On exchange of contracts a deposit of 10% is payable by you, such deposit being forfeited should you not proceed to completion.   If the seller agrees to accept a reduced deposit on exchange then, should you fail to complete your purchase, you will be required to pay the balance of the 10%. The completion date will be inserted just before exchange of contracts and we can discuss this prior to that time so that a date acceptable to both you and the seller can be fixed. You will be liable to pay daily interest at 4% above National Westminster Bank plc base rate from time to time if cleared funds are not made available to us in time to remit the completion monies to the seller’s solicitors’ bank account by 12 noon. If we cannot complete your purchase of the property due to the seller’s default, you will become entitled to the return of the deposit (and may be able to claim damages for your loss).   However, under the Standard Conditions of Sale, all or part of the deposit money can be used by the seller to pay the deposit on their new property, and only the remainder, if any, will be retained by their solicitors as “stakeholder” until we satisfactorily complete the purchase.   Whist this arrangement has become common practice, we must warn you that in the event of the matter not completing, it may be more difficult to obtain the repayment of the deposit money which has been used by the Seller in that way, than if the whole deposit was retained by their solicitors until completion. On the other hand, very few purchases totally fail to complete (though completion is occasionally delayed), and you may be prepared to take this risk rather than insisting that the seller incur the expense of obtaining separate bridging finance for the deposit on their new property. WORKSITE: 40434911/1   PAGE: 3 OF 15  Please note the property is being sold with Limited title guarantee as it is an executor selling it on behalf of an estate.   Limited title guarantee means that the seller of the property has no personal knowledge of the property for example Attorney, personal representative, trustee, repossession. Therefore they cannot give full title guarantee that the property is not subject to any financial charges and that no others have any rights over the property as they have no knowledge of the property. Further, they have not been able to provide us with the usual information a Seller would normally have and therefore the property is essentially being sold as seen. This is not uncommon in an executor sale. We have reported to you on the basis of the information we have received from the Seller's solicitor and you must satisfy yourself by inspecting the property and cross checking the information contained in the documents provided. Cladding  You are purchasing a property in a block of flats. Building Regulations have been changed since December 2019 to outlaw certain types of external wall systems (cladding), especially those which include aluminium composite materials. We are not surveyors and are not informed of the specific materials used in the construction of this building. Furthermore, we do not inspect properties so will only know if an external wall system is installed on the building if we are told. We will not seek to obtain an EWS1 form for your property unless we are specifically requested to do so by your lender or its valuer. Your property will have had building control sign off on completion of the original build and this will confirm that the property has been built in accordance with building regulations and therefore complied with the requirements at the point of construction. When you come to sell your buyer's solicitors and/or lender may require an EWS1 form, or equivalent. It may be that the building control sign off certificate is sufficient. The EWS process is the responsibility of the Landlord to undertake – not the Tenant/flat owner. However the cost of the process may be recovered via the service charge, if the lease allows. If a Tenant is trying to sell or mortgage or sublet, it cannot force its Landlord to get one and the lack of an EWS1 could prevent the Tenant from disposing of its interest. Having reviewed the searches we would wish to draw your attention to the following matters:  a) Local Search –   We have made a search in the Register of Local Land Charges and have raised enquiries with the local Council, and have obtained the following information which relates to the property which you are intending to buy.   A separate search would be needed to obtain information relating to neighbouring properties.  •   Planning –   We note that the local search indicates that various planning permission affect the property. We have reviewed the position and consider it to be satisfactory.  •   Building Regulations –   The local authority search did not reveal any alternations at the property which required building regulation consent.  •   Article 4 Directive –   The property is subject to an Article 4 Directive which restricts permitted development rights in a particular area. Since January 2018 express planning permission need to be made for any works you intend to carry out in the future.   The following website will provide you with further details of the importance of an Article 4 Directive:  https://historicengland.org.uk/advice/hpg/historic-environment/article4directions/  The seller's solicitors did not provide planning permission for the replacement windows and as such indemnity insurance will be obtained on completion in order to cover the risk. Please refer to the indemnity insurance section below for further information with regards to this.  •   Smoke Control Order –   The property is within an area subject to a Smoke Control Order where you can't emit smoke from a chimney unless you are burning an authorised fuel or using exempt   appliances   e.g.   burners   or   stoves. This is important because a Tree Preservation Order prohibits the cutting down, topping, lopping, uprooting, wilful damage or destruction of a tree, except with the consent of the Local Planning Authority or where the tree is dying, dead or dangerous or to prevent or abate a nuisance.   If a tree is destroyed, either in breach of the Order, or where the destruction   has   been   authorised   as   the   tree   was   dangerous,   the   owner   of   the   land   is automatically under a duty to replace the tree with another of an appropriate size and species unless the Local Planning Authority dispenses with this requirement.  •   Planning Designations and Proposals –   The search result did reveal planning designations and proposals. WORKSITE: 40434911/1   PAGE: 11 OF 15  LEGAL INDEMNITY INSURANCE  THE POSITION:  The Seller has failed to demonstrate that the necessary consent was obtained from the Local Authority for the replacement windows and as a consequence a legal indemnity insurance policy is put on risk to cover the issue. In the current economic climate this is a common way to address such issues. It does not mean that every buyer or every lender would accept the position, whilst most would it could affect your ability to re-sell or re-finance your property. The risk is that a third party could seek to establish that planning permission was not obtained for the replacement windows and seek to take retrospective legal action. The party may seek to compel you to comply with planning legislation or to restore the property to its original condition and or claim compensation. The insurance policy would not remove the problem, but it would give you a sum of money to defend any action. I enclose a copy of the draft policy for your information and confirm the fee for the same will be a one off fee of £156.30.   Please however note should you decide to sell the property in the future, a new buyer may insist the limit of indemnity is increased to the sale price at the time.   I am unable to confirm what the costs of this will be in the future.  BUY TO LET INVESTMENT  I understand you are purchasing the above property to let.   As a buy to let landlord, you will be at an increased risk of property fraud as you will not occupy the property as your main residence. I therefore wish to provide you with further information regarding this increased risk and some suggestions on how you might seek to mitigate being targeted by fraudsters. From recent case law, which you may have seen in the press, we can see that property fraud is increasing and is becoming ever more sophisticated. Property is usually the most valuable asset people own and is therefore an attractive target to fraudsters. A rising type of fraud seen by the Land Registry is where fraudsters first steal your identity and then sell or mortgage your property by pretending to be you. This is commonly known as 'property hijack'.   This is made easier where the property is let or empty and, for example, the legal owner has not safeguarded themselves by ensuring that their address for service of correspondence recorded at the Land Registry has been kept updated. Fortunately, this type of property fraud is rare. However, if you become a victim of this fraud, the effects can be devastating. Therefore, I recommend that you seek to protect yourself as much as possible and some suggestions on how to do this are as follows:- 1.   Ensure the property is registered. I will attend to this following completion of your purchase and (if it is not already) will ensure the property is registered at HM Land Registry as soon as possible. 2.   Ensure your contact details with the Land Registry are up-to-date at all times so the Registry can easily contact you. Please let me know before exchange of contracts if your proposed address for service is going to change. You can have up to three addresses on the register including an email address or an address abroad. The aim is to ensure that if the Land  ACTION:  You must not disclose the existence of the policy to a third party or make contact with anyone who could take action against you for a breach of etc as this might   invalidate the policy .

Sign   up   to   the   Land   Registry's   free   Property   Alert   service   at  https://propertyalert.landregistry.gov.uk.   The Land Registry will then send an email alert to  you when there is certain activity on your property (i.e. if someone tries to sell your property or offer your property as security for a mortgage). You will then be able to judge whether the activity is suspicious and seek advice, if necessary, from the Land Registry's fraud line. There is no fee for you to register this Property Alert directly with the Land Registry, provided that you do not live in the property that you wish to protect. 4.   Register a "restriction" against the property's title. The Land Registry will then be unable to register a sale or mortgage on your property unless a conveyancer or solicitor certifies the application was made by you. You can arrange this directly with the Land Registry using their guide available at   https://www.gov.uk/protect-land-property-from-fraud . There is no fee for you  to register this restriction directly with the Land Registry, provided that you do not live in the property you wish to protect. Alternatively, I would be happy to deal with this on your behalf. I confirm that this Firm's additional costs for preparing, submitting the application and checking that it has been registered correctly is £75.00 plus VAT. Please let me know before exchange of contracts if you would like me to arrange for the restriction to be registered. Please note that this may impact on a solicitors decision to deal with the future sale of the property if they are not absolutely comfortable with your identity. Thereafter, interest is variable at the discretion of the Lender.   After the initial fixed period, further periods of fixed rate interest may be agreed between you and the lender in writing from time to time. c) Should you redeem the mortgage either in whole or in part either as a consequence of selling the property, paying off a lump sum or charging to another lender you will incur a penalty payment.   The details of the early repayment charges are set out in the special conditions of the mortgage offer. d) The loan is repayable in full at the end of the 21-year period with interest payable in monthly instalments. Initially the instalments will be £681.29 per month until 31 January 2026. Thereafter, the monthly instalments will vary, and the Lender will recalculate the amount as a result of changes in the rate of interest from time to time.   You will be required to pay the instalments by bank standing order. Failure to pay any instalments will entitle the Lender to call for immediate repayment of the entire loan. The lender will advise you on or about 31 March in each year during the term of the monthly instalments payable during the 2 month period commencing on 1 April in that year so as to ensure that the loan and all interest is paid in full by the expiry o the term.
